Package: margot.sim
Type: Package
Title: Simulate Longitudinal Data with Observational Shadows and Monte Carlo Evaluation
Version: 0.1.3
Authors@R: 
    person("Joseph", "Bulbulia", email = "joseph.bulbulia@gmail.com", role = c("aut", "cre"),
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0002-5861-2056"))
Description: Extensions to the margot package for simulating longitudinal data 
    using Structural Causal Models (SCMs). Provides sophisticated capabilities 
    for applying various observational shadows (measurement error, missingness, 
    selection bias) to simulated data, running Monte Carlo simulations to evaluate 
    statistical estimators, supporting flexible non-normal distributions, and creating 
    a unified framework for causal inference method evaluation. The shadow framework 
    is inspired by Plato's Allegory of the Cave, representing observed data as 
    distorted reflections of true causal processes. Key methodological foundations 
    include: Pearl (2009) <doi:10.1017/CBO9780511803161> "Causality: Models, 
    Reasoning, and Inference"; Hern√°n and Robins (2020) <https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/miguel-hernan/causal-inference-book/> 
    "Causal Inference: What If"; Little and Rubin (2002) <doi:10.1002/9781119013563> 
    "Statistical Analysis with Missing Data"; Carroll et al. (2006) <doi:10.1201/9781420010138> 
    "Measurement Error in Nonlinear Models".
